    "content": "And The Man Smoked Prologue Madhav sat across from me â€” uninvited, as always â€” in that quiet hour when the world feels like itâ€™s running out of breath. He didnâ€™t speak. He just watched, eyes glimmering with that infuriating mix of knowing and indifference. I broke the silence the only way I knew how.\nWith smoke.\nMonologue And the man smoked.\nNot for pleasure. Not for pain. But because silence demanded punctuation. The world had grown too loud, too insistent â€” and smoke was the only language left that didnâ€™t need translation.\nHe drew the fire close to his lips, felt it bite, then fade into surrender. Each drag, a question. Each exhale, an answer he didnâ€™t believe.\nHeâ€™d seen too much of timeâ€™s crooked humour â€” how it gave, only to take, how it smiled while twisting the knife. He had stopped chasing meaning long ago; now he merely kept it at bay, like a stray dog that once knew his name.\nThe ember glowed like a dying sun in his hand, a tiny apocalypse contained. He thought of the people who once tried to save him â€” how they mistook his smoke for decay, when it was only his way of praying.\nTo what, he no longer knew. Gods? Ghosts? Or just the echo of a man who once believed he could change the ending?\nThe wind came, soft and uncaring, and the ash drifted down like tired snow. He watched it fall, and smiled â€” that crooked, weary smile of a man whoâ€™s made peace with his own undoing.\nAnd when the last curl of smoke rose and vanished, he didnâ€™t mourn it. He simply lit another.\nEpilogue Madhav finally spoke. â€œStill searching for salvation in smoke?â€\nI laughed, hoarse and hollow. â€œNot salvation, Madhav. Justâ€¦ companionship.â€\nHe smiled that quiet, cruel smile â€” the kind gods reserve for fools they secretly admire.\nAnd for a moment, the smoke between us looked like mercy.",
